Multi-Tiered Datastore
A multi-tiered datastore stores data across different storage tiers (hot, warm, cold) based on access frequency, performance needs, and cost.
Hot data stays in fast storage, while cold/archival data moves to cheaper storage.

Storage Tiers :

| Tier     | Storage                          | Performance | Cost      | Use Case                                  |
| -------- | -------------------------------- | ----------- | --------- |------- |
| **Hot**  | In-memory (Redis), SSDs          | âš¡ High      | ğŸ’° High   | Active sessions, real-time queries
| **Warm** | HDDs, NAS                        | âš¡ Medium    | ğŸ’° Medium | Historical but relevant data 
| **Cold** | Cloud archive (S3 Glacier, Tape) | ğŸ¢ Low      | ğŸ’° Low    | Backups, compliance, rarely accessed logs


Example
MongoDB Atlas â†’ Hot data in cluster, old data in S3.
AWS S3 â†’ Standard (hot), Standard-IA (warm), Glacier (cold).

Benefits
Cost-efficient storage
High performance for hot data
Scales for petabyte datasets

**ğŸ‘‰ In short: Multi-tiered datastores put the right data on the right storage at the right time.**